    opportunities: ["Expansion into export markets with the new manufacturing facility.", "Growing demand for premium home decor and kitchenware in India.", "Potential to scale private label business with retailers like Westside and Lifestyle."],
    outlook: "## What Happens Next?\nThe IPO closes on June 19, and allotment is expected by June 23. If oversubscribed, retail investors may face a lottery system for allotment. The shares are likely to list on the NSE and BSE by June 26, depending on market conditions. \n\nPost-listing, the focus will shift to Clay Craft’s execution of its expansion plans. The new manufacturing facility in Rajasthan is expected to be operational by Q1 FY26, which could boost revenue by 25-30% if demand holds up. However, investors should keep an eye on:\n- **Quarterly Results:** Any signs of margin pressure or slowing growth could spook the market.\n- **Competitor Moves:** How peers like Cera and HSIL respond to Clay Craft’s expansion.\n- **Consumer Sentiment:** Discretionary spending trends will be critical for the company’s performance.\n\nFor now, the IPO seems to have struck a chord with retail investors, but the real test will come post-listing. If the GMP holds, we could see a strong debut, but sustainability will depend on the company’s ability to deliver on its growth promises.",
    conclusion: "Clay Craft India’s IPO is a classic case of a mid-sized player trying to make its mark in a competitive industry. The valuation is reasonable, the GMP is strong, and the growth story is compelling—at least on paper. But as with any IPO, the devil lies in the details. \n\nFor retail investors, the IPO offers a chance to bet on India’s growing appetite for premium home decor and tableware. However, the risks are real, and the company’s ability to execute its expansion plans will determine whether this IPO is a success or just another flash in the pan. \n\nIf you’re subscribing, do so with a long-term view. The next few quarters will reveal whether Clay Craft can turn its IPO buzz into sustainable growth—or if it’s just another case of hype over substance.",
